censor the other at a time when some say students, rather than being challenged to wrestle with difficult issues and ideas, are being quarantined from them. He uniquely frames the examination: our ability to think rationally is inhibited when our identity is fiercely connected to an issue of perceived social justice or injustice, and our proclivity to see in-groups and out-groups – us versus them – is obvious. According to Stern, the campus is the best place to mine this conflict and our intense views about it to help future generations do what they are supposed to do: think. The Conflict over the Conflict shows how this is possible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAcademic freedom. 0aArab-Israeli conflict. 0aEducation, HigherxPolitical aspects. 0aFreedom of speech. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  aAntisemitism.  aBDS.  aIsrael.  aJewish.  aPalestine.  aZionism.  aacademic boycott.  aacademic freedom.  acampus activism.  acensorship.  acollege.  adifficult issues.  afree speech.  ahate studies.  ahigher education.  apeace.  auniversity.1 aStrossen, Nadine.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753609140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487536091423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487536091.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles